<TEXT>
president alberto fujimori whose country is 
starved for foreign capital says he will ease restrictions on 
foreign investment in perus petroleum fishing mining and tourism 
industries 
fujimori said wednesday that he would promote legislation to 
speed up negotiations with foreign investors and eliminate laws 
that limit the potential profitability of these investments 
foreign corporations will soon be able to repatriate profits 
from their peruvian operations fujimori told a luncheon given by 
the american chamber of commerce in lima 
upon taking office on july 28 fujimori began a series of 
measures to curb hyperinflation and open perus economy to world 
markets 
the measures have included drastic rises in the costs of 
government services and the end of most price controls and 
subsidies 
fujimori also slashed import tariffs forcing perus 
traditionally highly protected industries to compete with foreign 
products 
the measures sent prices soaring 397 percent in august but 
prices in september are expected to rise less than 5 percent 
the austerity plan has left perus economy virtually paralyzed 
many factories are closed and thousands of small businesses are 
expected to go bankrupt 
at wednesdays lunch fujimori assured businessmen they were 
safe from the risk of of expropriation illegal change of 
ownership or conversion into national currency of foreign profits 
in peru 
fujimoris predecessor alan garcia threatened to nationalize 
various foreign concerns in peru these included the mines of 
southern peru copper corporation the largest us company 
operating in peru 
fujimori said the results of his austerity measures were 
encouraging 
he said peru needed fiscal and monetary discipline to create a 
climate of confidence for foreign investment 
president george bush has said prosperity in latin america 
depends on trade not aid fujimori said we agree on that 
one 
fujimoris prime minister juan hurtado miller is in washington 
this week for talks with the international monetary fund 
peru cut relations with the imf in 1987 after unilaterally 
limiting payments on its 20 billion foreign debt the year before 
hurtado hopes to come home with fresh loans if the imf approves 
of perus austerity measures imf officials have indicated they 
will 
</TEXT>
