<TEXT>
thousands of filipinos are fleeing 
the persian gulf area but thousands more are still flocking to the 
middle east searching for jobs to escape poverty and hopelessness 
in this troubled island nation 
over the last year an average of 15000 filipinos a month left 
for jobs in the gulf and that figure still holds true despite the 
crisis precipitated by iraqs aug 2 invasion of kuwait according 
to the staterun philippine overseas employment agency 
chartered jets which recently flew hundreds of exhausted and 
penniless refugees home from camps in jordan have been returning to 
the middle east packed with new jobseekers 
if you remain in our country you will never prosper said 
letty solis whose mechanic husband leopoldo is still looking for 
work after returning from kuwait last month 
statistics show why filipinos leave families behind to work in 
the gulf 
the unemployment rate here stands at more than 8 percent and is 
expected to increase as thousands of workers return from kuwait and 
iraq 
before the crisis an estimated 90000 filipinos were working in 
kuwait and iraq about 16500 have returned to the philippines 
the mimimum pay you get here is not enough to buy the basics 
for yourself much less your family said miguel ramos 35 an 
unemployed electrician who has just been hired by a firm in saudi 
arabia 
a job here for ramos would pay about 88 a month he expects to 
make more than four times that in the gulf 
ramos acknowledged its a gamble i know its risky but id 
rather take it besides things are so unstable in our country 
anyway that it doesnt make any difference where you are if you 
are used to hardships then it doesnt matter if theres war 
president corazon aquinos government has promised to help 
workers who fled kuwait and iraq find other jobs abroad but of the 
16500 workers who have come home since the invasion fewer than 
100 have found new jobs overseas through government efforts 
for most conditions are desperate many of those who left 
kuwait lost most of their savings when banks wre closed and the 
kuwaiti dinar declared invalid 
gulf labor laws make it nearly impossible for refugees from 
kuwait to land jobs in saudi arabia the united arab emirates or 
other gulf countries without first returning to the philippines 
every day the semiprivate overseas workers welfare 
adminstration headquarters teems with returnees inquiring about 
jobs abroad and applying for 120 in emergency displacement loans 
which returning workers are authorized to obtain 
that would feed an averagesized filipino family of five for two 
weeks many must borrow money or move in with friends and relatives 
after years of relative comfort and prosperity abroad 
i will still go back there if things normalize said mars 
ariola who worked in kuwait as a truck driver for five years if 
i cannot get into the middle east then i will try europe or any 
other country 
except for banning travel to kuwait iraq and parts of saudi 
arabia the government has done nothing to prevent thousands of its 
citizens from working in the persian gulf despite fears that the 
region may explode into fullscale war 
filipinos working in the middle east send home about 13 
billion a year a major source of foreign exchange remittances 
from kuwait and iraq accounted for about 5 percent of the foreign 
exchange official figures show 
we have to consider the need for them to earn and also for the 
country to get revenues from the foreign exchange earnings of our 
workers presidential spokesman adolf azcuna said we just hope 
that the workers will be deployed to areas far from trouble 
