the persian gulf crisis is forcing 
saudi arabia which traditionally has relied on quiet diplomacy to 
take aggressive steps even against arab states once considered 
allies 
jordan and yemen have already experienced the newfound saudi 
punitive power indications are that the palestine liberation 
organization or at least its leader yasser arafat will be next 
sudan another recipient of saudi financial aid that has not 
broken with iraq over its aug 2 invasion of kuwait could soon see 
its relations with riyadh sour 
there will be a settlement of accounts when this is over a 
saudi diplomatic official said wednesday we have to stand up for 
principle it is no more mr nice guy there is no longer the 
fear of offending arabs 
as saudi arabia deliberately strains relations with some 
traditional arab allies it is moving quickly to improve its 
position on the world stage reestablishing ties with moscow and 
beijing 
senior saudi officials believe the crisis has dashed any hopes 
for arab unity and created an atmosphere in which arab states will 
seek to bolster their standing outside the region 
the bubble of panarabism is burst said the official 
speaking on condition of anonymity now maybe all of us can be 
more honest 
