<TEXT>
new census bureau figures show that the gap 
between the rich and the poor is widening says the chairman of the 
congressional joint economic committee 
those at the top of the scale are receiving an everlarger 
share of the pie rep lee hamilton dind said wednesday after 
the bureau released its annual report on income and poverty 
meanwhile families in the middle and at the bottom are barely 
keeping ahead of inflation hamilton said the gap between the 
rich and the poor is widening when it should be shrinking 
robert greenstein executive director of a liberal research 
group the center on budget and policy priorities said the 128 
percent poverty rate reported by the bureau is a bad sign 
with the economy running out of steam and a new recession 
threatening the poverty rate is likely to start rising again 
greenstein said that means an already high poverty rate is 
likely to climb higher and if the recession is a deep one it could 
reach poverty levels not seen for a quarter of a century 
both liberals and conservatives continued to clamor for a change 
in the way the census bureau figures out who is poor 
for the third year in a row the bureau said the decline in the 
poverty rate between 1988 and 1989 was so small that it was not 
statistically significant the 1988 rate was 13 percent 
the bureau said 315 million americans were below the poverty 
level last year for a family of four that level is an annual 
income of 12675 in 1988 317 million were below it 
it is time to update our official poverty measure to provide a 
more accurate reflection of todays economic needs hamilton 
said 
a joint economic committee study last year suggested that the 
poverty thresholds might increase as much as 50 percent if they 
took into account such things as the increasing share of income 
that is now paid for housing 
on the other hand kate obeirne deputy director for domestic 
policy studies at the conservative heritage foundation said 
owing to the method they use the census bureau dramatically 
overstates the number of people in poverty 
the problem she said is that the bureau counts only money as 
income and does not include such things as food stamps and medicaid 
and medicare benefits 
in an appendix to its report the census bureau said that with 
the addition of these and other noncash items the poverty rate 
would be as low as 104 percent 
both daniel weinberg chief of the housing and household 
economic statistics division of the bureau and greenstein said 
that adopting such an alternative method would not affect the trend 
of poverty rates 
the bureau reported that median household income in 1989 was 
28910 up 13 percent from 1988 after adjusting for rising living 
costs household income had been unchanged in the previous two 
years 
the bureau said the wealthiest onefifth of households received 
468 percent of the income while this was no higher than in 1988 
it was significantly higher than the percentages of 442 percent in 
1979 and 43 percent in 1969 
those on the lower rungs of the economic ladder received 
somewhat lower shares of the aggregate income 
there seems little doubt that the income distribution has 
become somewhat less equal over the past 20 years the bureau 
said it said the reasons for this are not clear 
</TEXT>
