<TEXT>
the air force is estimating that the cost of 
its c17 transport has risen to 400 million per plane and fears 
the aircrafts manufacturer mcdonnell douglas may go bankrupt by 
years end a house committee chairman says 
in a letter released wednesday rep john dingell dmich 
cited the companys cost overruns and excessive work hours as 
evidence of a management collapse in the program to build 120 
of the widebody planes 
dingell based his assessment on internal pentagon documents 
reports from mcdonnell douglas and an inquiry conducted by the 
staff of the house energy and commerce subcommittee on oversight 
and investigations dingell is chairman of both the full committee 
and the subcommittee 
an unidentified air force official who had been working with the 
company told the panels staff that in his opinion mcdonnell 
douglas management was committing corporate suicide dingell 
said 
the official said the options left to the air force were to 
either suspend or significantly cut progress payments on the c17 
program but a financial analysis of the company concluded that if 
the payments were cut mcdonnell douglas might go bankrupt 
regardless of the progress payments issue the air force 
believes that mcdonnell douglas may go bankrupt by the end of the 
year dingell said in the letter 
he also cited internal pentagon reports that estimated the 
c17s cost at more than 400 million per plane air force 
officials testified to congress last june that the plane which 
will replace the current c141 aircraft will cost an estimated 
249 million 
richard hill a mcdonnell douglas spokesman in long beach 
calif said the company has estimated that when the c17 program 
is completed the cost will be below the ceiling levels in the 
government contract 
hill acknowledged past reports of schedule problems and delays 
but said that since november 1989 the company has met every 
milestone set in the past few months the landing gear was placed 
on the airplane its going to fly in june the progress is 
there 
hill declined to comment on the bankruptcy issue 
mcdonnell douglas in an internal report dated april 1990 
estimated a cost overrun of 836 million on the c17 contract in 
the last month however the contractor spent 118 million to 
complete work that was estimated at 47 million 
overhead expenses of 51 million in the internal report far 
exceeded the cost of 15 million while administrative expenses of 
9 million were about three times the projected cost of 3 million 
dingell in his letter to rep les aspin dwis chairman of 
the house armed services committee bristled at the number of hours 
it took to produce work that mcdonnell douglas own industrial 
engineers said should take only one 
for example he said 258 assembly hours were spent on the 
aircraft when one was determined to be sufficient 
we found an appalling picture in factory labor performance 
dingell said 
problems with the program were raised in june when the air force 
decided to take away the approval it had previously granted to 
mcdonnell douglas on its purchasing system for the c17 
the decision meant the company must get air force approval for 
purchases in excess of 100000 the air force told congress that 
the action would not delay the program 
nevertheless concerns about the program prompted the senate in 
