<TEXT>
security forces in zaire continue to violently 
repress government opponents despite recent promises to expand the 
oneparty political system and make other reforms amnesty 
international charged today 
although abuses have diminished in recent years incidents of 
banishment torture and detentions without charge or trial are 
coming to light the international human rights group said in a 
report 
appeals to the government to investigate these incidents have 
been ignored and the authorities have shown themselves unwilling to 
take disciplinary action against security forces the group 
said 
the government of president mobutu sese seko which has ruled 
the central african country since 1965 last spring promised a 
series of political reforms 
in april mobutu made a series of improvements including giving 
citizens the right to form opposition political parties and trade 
unions 
in may he promised an end to internal banishment and 
incommunicado detention and the release of all uncharged political 
prisoners pledges which remain unfulfilled said the londonbased 
organization 
the zairean security services which are directly responsible 
to the president maintain extensive powers to arrest and detain 
political suspects and hold them in arbitrary and incommunicado 
detention where many have been illtreated and tortured amnesty 
said 
security forces involved in the abuses include a special service 
responsible for immigration an elite presidential guard and a 
paramilitary police group which helps to control borders it said 
since january 1988 amnesty has received reports of several 
hundred people arrested and imprisoned for political reasons the 
report says 
most of those targeted are members of the opposition union for 
democracy and social progress in july more than 12 members were 
arrested and some were allegedly beaten while holding a meeting 
said the human rights group it did not detail whether the members 
were detained 
security forces have also killed government opponents the 
report says 
most recently the forces were implicated in the reported 
killing of at least 12 students on may 1112 at lubumbashi 
university it says 
the government initially denied responsibility for the killings 
but a parliamentary inquiry led to the arrests of the governor of 
the shaba region and other government officials 
belgium zaires former colonial ruler has called for an 
international investigation of the incident and zaires refusal has 
helped sour relations between the countries amnesty said 
in addition at least five students were reportedly killed in 
february 1989 when soldiers dispersed unarmed demonstrators at 
kinshasa said the report 
