<TEXT>
president bush is warning that hardfought 
clean air legislation may fall apart unless congress steps up 
efforts to work out a compromise 
the president wednesday bemoaned the slow progress of 
housesenate negotiations on a final clean air package and offered 
a compromise proposal to help break the logjam that once again 
has appeared 
house and senate members have been struggling since early july 
to resolve differences in separate clean air bills that won 
overwhelming approval in each chamber earlier this year 
the legislation which calls for tough new air pollution 
controls on factories electric utilities and automobiles 
represents the first tightening of federal air pollution laws in 13 
years 
but the talks have bogged down on details of the massive 
legislation 
in a letter to the leaders of the house and senate negotiating 
teams the president said the talks have strayed away from what the 
administration wants and that the slow progress may 
jeopardize enactment of a bill before congress adjourns next 
month 
the administrations new plan took provisions from both the 
house and senate bills did not contain any new initiatives 
rep john dingell dmich chairman of the house delegation 
said he wondered why the administration didnt send up the proposal 
when the issue was before the house last spring 
environmentalists also were not impressed by the white house 
initiative they picked the weakest part of each bill except on 
acid rain said daniel weiss who has followed the clean air 
debate for the sierra club 
administration officials said their new proposal was 3 billion 
cheaper than either the house or senate bill the white house all 
along has expressed concern about the cost of the widereaching air 
pollution controls estimating that both the senate and house 
versions will cost industry more than 25 billion a year when all 
the new requirements take effect 
while there is general agreement between both the house and 
senate on tough new controls to reduce acid rain toxic industrial 
chemical releases and urban smog disagreements remain on details 
in each of these areas 
were concerned that theyre not taking action fast enough 
said william rosenberg an assistant administrator at the 
environmental protection agency he characterized the 
administration proposal as an attempt to bridge the gap between 
the house and senate 
a white house official acknowledged that the proposal in part 
was an attempt to get the bush administration more closely involved 
in the clean air discussions on capitol hill 
the president has been frozen out in the process and the 
results have been stalemated said the official who spoke under 
the condition that he not be named he said the view from the white 
house was that the clock is ticking and the conferees were not 
delivering 
earlier this month the negotiators announced a tentative 
agreement on reducing smogcausing pollution from industrial 
sources and on permitting requirements for industry previously 
they reached agreement on how to deal with chemicals that damage 
the atmospheric ozone layer 
but the two sides have yet to take up in detail a number of 
other controversial issues including how far to go to ensure the 
public protection from toxic chemical releases by industry and 
whether to provide jobloss assistance to workers who become 
unemployed because of the tougher pollution controls 
