<TEXT>
the vatican today welcomed the soviet 
unions new law on freedom of conscience saying it renders 
justice to millions of believers 
the freedom of conscience law promised by president mikhail s 
gorbachev when he met with pope john paul ii at the vatican in 
december was approved wednesday by the soviet legislature 
chief vatican spokesman joaquin navarro expressed great 
satisfaction and said the vatican is now looking forward to the 
approval of the various articles in the legislation 
the law formally ending decades of religious repression 
forbids the government from interfering with religious activities 
improves the legal status of religious organizations and gives 
soviet citizens the right to study religion in homes and in private 
schools 
it also paves the way for legalization of the ukrainian catholic 
church whose suppression by stalin in 1947 has been a major thorn 
in vaticansoviet relations under the new law the church can 
apply to local authorities to regain lawful status 
gorbachevs historic meeting with the pope has already led to 
the establishment of official ties between the vatican and moscow 
a resolution of the ukrainian issue could lead to full ties and a 
papal visit 
