<TEXT>
a blaze that destroyed an unfinished subway 
tunnel and shut down a major highway last summer probably was 
caused by a cutting torch officials say 
the july 13 fire in the downtown metro rail tunnel caused no 
injuries or deaths but produced more than 2 million damage the 
750foot tunnel which passes under us 101 partially collapsed 
the freeway was closed for days until it could be shored up 
the report by the socalled independent investigation team was 
commissioned by rail construction corp a subsidiary of the los 
angeles county transportation commission 
the investigation did not rule out arson but said the fire most 
likely began with the use of a torchtto trim steel spikes in the 
tunnel 
the tunnel was shored up with timber a polyethylene membrane 
was installed over the timber to keep methane gas in the soil from 
entering the tunnel 
the report said the torch flame or hot metal slag probably 
caused a timber to smolder seven or eight hours later the fire 
burned through the membrane and spread rapidly through the two 
materials 
the report said two earlier fires in the same 24hour period had 
been quickly extinguished 
the fire department hasnt completed its investigation and the 
district attorney is investigating whether safety violations were a 
factor 
ed mcspedon rail constructions president and chief executive 
officer said wednesday the firm has implemented a fire safety plan 
that includes a constant fire watch at construction sites 
in the future precast concrete liners will be used instead of 
the timber and polyethylene combination mcspedon said 
the first 44mile segment of the 33 billion subway is 
scheduled to open in 1994 it is 135 million over budget and 18 
months behind schedule metro rail will eventually stretch 17 miles 
from downtown to the san fernando valley 
