a federal judge says he is going to resign from 
the bench mainly because hes unhappy with sentencing guidelines 
enacted by congress 
us district judge j lawrence irving said wednesday he plans 
to notify president bush that he will resign effective dec 31 
irving 55 a 1982 reagan appointee said the strict guidelines 
which sharply reduce a judges discretion in sentencing convicted 
criminals have taken much of the enjoyment out of being a federal 
judge 
to me the job just isnt as much fun as it used to be he 
said the purpose of the guidelines is admirable to do away 
with disparity in sentencing it just doesnt work out that way 
in a march 1988 case irving declared the sentencing guidelines 
unconstitutional joining three other federal judges in san diego 
who had issued similar rulings they were among the first in the 
nation to challenge the standards which were upheld by the us 
supreme court in january 1989 
irving said he believes hes the first judge in the nation to 
quit because of the rules 
federal judges appointed by the president and approved by the 
senate have life tenure they earn about 96000 a year and that 
will rise to 120653 in february 
the sentencing reform act of 1984 established a sentencing 
commission that set the new guidelines which took effect in 
november 1987 
the guidelines use a point system based mainly on the severity 
of the crime to determine sentences a persons background role in 
the crime past record or remorse cannot be used to reduce the 
sentence below the minimum guideline 
it used to be that a judge could do some good in sentencing 
by being lenient when leniency was called for he said now i 
cant do that 
ill tell you it really tugs at your heart when you have to 
sentence a firsttime offender to a 10year minimummandatory 
sentence or a 15year minimummandatory with no parole 
