the widow of a kentucky coal miner said today 
federal inspectors are partly to blame for a methane explosion that 
killed 10 miners because of their lax inspection policy 
sharon scott 36 said the mine safety and health administration 
knew prior to the september 1989 blast near wheatcroft ky that 
water had backed up in the mine jeopardizing ventilation 
msha inspectors routinely failed to order remedial measures 
for safety violations that they did see mrs scott told the 
house education and labor committees health and safety 
subcommittee 
william j tattersall assistant labor secretary for mine safety 
and health acknowledged there were shortcomings in mshas 
enforcement of regulations at the pyro mining co mine where the 
blast occurred 
but he said those shortcomings did not cause the explosion 
tattersall said enforcement had been stepped up at the mine but 
the sanctions imposed by inspectors were not strong enough to 
change pyros poor attitude about safety poor safety management 
and disregard of the law 
james greenlee executive vice president of costain coal inc 
based in evansville ind and owner of pyro mining declined to 
comment at length on the hearing obviously we would not agree 
with mr tattersalls analysis of our performance he said 
the federal government has proposed fines of more than 500000 
against pyro for 121 alleged violations of federal safety laws 
some of them which allegedly were directly linked to the explosion 
mrs scott who is a coal miner was working in a different part 
of the mine when the blast occurred and she escaped she fought 
back sobs as she told the committee about the events leading up to 
the explosion that killed her husband curtis and nine others 
she said that pyro managers frequently made miners hide safety 
violations from federal inspectors on one occasion mrs scott 
said she was ordered to stick blasting caps inside her blouse so 
that the inspectors would not discover that blasting had been done 
i do not believe that msha should be held responsible for 
facts that were hidden from them by mine management mrs scott 
said but she added that federal inspectors simply overlooked many 
dangerous violations 
i believe this lax inspection policy and carefree attitude 
about ordering management to correct dangers makes msha partially 
responsible for the deaths of my husband and friends she said 
