<TEXT>
president mikhail s gorbachev began using his 
sweeping new powers to rescue the collapsing soviet economy on 
thursday ordering businesses to fulfill supply contracts and the 
government to ensure distribution 
but it was far from clear that people would comply with his 
order many are uncertain how they will fit in the market economy 
gorbachev is trying to establish and they find it more profitable 
to trade goods on the black market rather than distribute them in 
the established structure 
a western specialist called the order a waste of time 
in his first decree since the supreme soviet legislature on 
monday granted him new powers to shore up the economy and maintain 
law and order gorbachev said told government businesses 
regardless of their administrative subordination and location 
to preserve economic ties he said the businesses should meet all 
contract obligations for raw materials and other goods in the last 
quarter of this year and throughout 1991 
it is during that period that the country will be trying to 
switch from a centrally planned to a market economy under a plan 
the supreme soviet is to select after oct 15 
gorbachevs decree read on the nightly tv newscast vremya 
and released by the tass news agency was an attempt to preserve 
the status quo at a time when many businesses are trying to bypass 
moscow and trade directly with each other 
the restive republics for instance have been signing economic 
cooperation agreements in a preliminary step toward a common 
market that leaves the moscow ministries which since the 1920s 
have issued fiveyear plans that told thousands of factories farms 
and businesses what to produce where to sell it and how much to 
charge out of the picture 
gorbachev said it was impermissible that managers had 
disrupted economic ties and referred to the extraordinary nature 
of the situation 
in a harkening back to bolshevik appeals to the proletariat 
gorbachev urged workers to join their bosses in making sure 
contracts are kept he also said the council of ministers the 
soviet cabinet should if necessary introduce a special regime 
for the operation of railways and other allstate lifesustaining 
systems of the country 
bottlenecks in railroad deliveries in part caused by a shortage 
of railroad cars have reportedly disrupted the distribution of 
food and other goods nationwide soviets face shortages of housing 
food and consumer goods and the government daily izvestia on 
thursday warned that power failures are possible this winter 
because fuel reserves are running low and twothirds of power 
equipment is worn out and unreliable 
jan vanous director of the economics research firm planecon 
called gorbachevs decree misdirected 
what the soviets need is price liberalization vanous said 
in a telephone interview from his washington office passing some 
decree on relations between enterprises is a waste of time 
several proposals before the supreme soviet legislature would 
free prices of goods now set by the government the most radical 
blueprint written by economist stanislav shatalin calls for 
junking the central planning system and moving to a market economy 
within 500 days by selling factories to private owners and breaking 
up collective farms 
gorbachev had said he would not wait for the economic rescue 
plan to be approved before issuing decrees to stablize the economy 
but vanous said gorbachev is making a mistake 
what is needed for stabilization is destabilization unleash 
market forces and let the economy take a deep plunge then it 
stabilizes he said 
several statistics point to a breakdown of the system 
interior ministry officials said investigators have found 
corruption at half the 160000 businesses they inspected this year 
and incidents of serious embezzlement are running at twice last 
years level 
from january through june the gross national product dropped 1 
percent and labor productivity fell 15 percent government reports 
have said at the same time the government printed 9 percent more 
rubles and the average wage for industrial and service workers shot 
up 
