<TEXT>
the latest republican proposal for breaking 
the deadlock over deficit reduction would give president bush the 
capitalgains tax cut he demands only the method would be 
different 
instead of excluding a flat 30 percent of longterm capital 
gains from taxation as the president proposes the new plan would 
exclude an amount that would vary with the inflation rate 
backers of a capitalgains cut say the new proposal called 
indexing would increase incentives for investment although in the 
short run the punch might not be as strong as under bushs 
plan opponents who have shown no sign of endorsing the new 
proposal say it has the same flaw as its predecessor the lions 
share of the tax cut would go to those with incomes over 100000 a 
year 
its still a capitalgains cut rep leon panetta dcalif 
chairman of the house budget committee an opponent of a reduction 
said after the indexing proposal was offered to deficit negotiators 
earlier in the week 
indexing is designed to prevent taxation of capital gains that 
result only from inflation 
present law taxes capital gains which are profits from the 
sale of investments at the same rates applying to wages and other 
income 15 percent 28 percent and 33 percent 
assume for example that a piece of real estate was bought in 
1983 for 50000 and sold in 1990 for 100000 under present law 
the 50000 profit would be taxed fully a person in the 28 percent 
bracket would pay 14000 
under bushs original plan 30 percent of the 50000 or 
15000 would be excluded from taxation resulting in a tax of 
9800 for a person in the 28 percent bracket 
because consumer prices have risen about 25 percent since 1983 
onequarter of the 50000 profit is illusory that portion has not 
increased the sellers purchasing power at all 
under a proposal for fully indexing against inflation that 25 
percent would not be taxed leaving the seller in the 28 percent 
bracket with a tax bill of 10500 instead of 14000 
sellers of longheld property might be better off with indexing 
than under bushs original plan in other cases a flat exclusion 
would be more profitable 
details of the indexing proposal being considered by the 
negotiators have not been made public leaving key questions 
unanswered would investors be protected fully against inflation 
or perhaps only against inflation above 2 percent or 3 percent a 
year would capital losses caused solely by inflation by 
deductible 
before 1986 only 40 percent of gains were taxed with a maximum 
incometax rate of 50 percent that had the effect of a top 
capitalgains tax rate of 20 percent 
if bushs original proposal for a 30 percent exclusion were to 
become law the richest americans who pay a maximum incometax 
rate of 28 percent would pay 196 percent on capital gains 
however some uppermiddleincome people who face a top rate of 33 
percent would pay a top capitalgains rate of 231 percent 
past attempts to index capital gains have prompted protests that 
this would discriminate against other investors whose money is in 
savings accounts or other investments that also are hurt by 
inflation 
