<TEXT>
the world bank signalled for the first time 
thursday that it may not have sufficient resources to handle the 
economic shocks resulting from the persian gulf crisis without 
appealing to rich countries for extra donations 
officials of both the world bank and its sister lending 
organization the international monetary fund expressed worries 
about the possibility that the turmoil in the mideast could result 
in a global recession 
but the two institutions continued to insist that such a 
calamity could be avoided with sensible policies to control the 
inflation expected to result from the doubling of oil prices since 
iraqs aug 2 invasion of kuwait 
we face the risks of recession and higher inflation it is 
time for a steady response we need to maintain confidence imf 
managing director michel camdessus said at the close of the 45th 
annual meetings of the two institutions 
countries will suffer from the gulf crisis but this is 
manageable as long as debtor nations follow good policies and the 
international support matches the efforts of the countries 
themselves camdessus said 
world bank president barber conable said that if oil prices 
remain at current high levels over the next three months then his 
institution would likely not have sufficient resources to cushion 
the impact on developing countries 
he said that if that proves to be the case he would seek 
approval from the countries that make up the banks board of 
directors to establish a special fund for voluntary contributions 
from oilrich nations and others 
the money would be used to provide nointerest loans to nations 
having the greatest difficulty coping with the jump in oil prices 
and other economic fallout from the persian gulf crisis 
conable did not mention any possible candidates for such aid 
but a world bank report earlier in the week singled out 10 
countries whose economies stood to suffer the most from the iraqi 
invasion 
the list included jordan turkey and egypt the nations the bush 
administration has been focusing its fundraising effort on in a 
belief that without significant aid the resolve of these nations to 
support the campaign against saddam hussein could crumble 
the world bank report also listed morocco bangladesh india 
pakistan the philippines sri lanka and sudan as countries that 
would be seriously affected from such factors as higher oil prices 
loss of export markets and returning refugees 
if the price of oil stays up and there continues to be turmoil 
and uncertainty and an impact on the global economy clearly it 
will have a major impact on significant parts of the developing 
world conable told reporters 
his comments thursday represented a change from an earlier 
stance that the world bank did not need to create programs and 
could handle the crisis with existing resources 
in part the change of view reflected the escalating economic 
fallout that has seen world oil prices climb toward 40 per barrel 
other world bank officials suggested that the proposed new 
lending program could be used to disburse funds raised by the gulf 
crisis financial coordination group a steering committee unveiled 
in a speech by president bush to the opening session of the 
imfworld bank on tuesday however they said discussions on this 
possibility were still in a very preliminary stage 
on monday both the imf and the world bank endorsed usbacked 
proposals to boost their lending in response to the gulf crisis 
but those increases were to be made in the context of existing 
programs at both institutions 
on another matter both camdessus and conable said they had held 
discussions with a delegation from the soviet union which was 
attending this years annual meeting for the first time 
however both officials indicated it would be some time before 
the soviet union would qualify for membership something the 
soviets desire because it would allow them to tap the huge loan 
resources of both agencies 
while membership is not immediately possible both conable and 
camdessus said their institutions would provide technical advice to 
help the soviets in the massive job of reforming their economic 
system 
