indian refugees angered by harsh conditions 
and long delays in a desert transit camp attacked an airportbound 
van thursday staged demonstrations and angrily confronted a 
visiting official 
the incidents betrayed a growing frustration among the nearly 
14000 refugees at the camp some of whom have waited up to eight 
days in the heat and dust with only cucumbers tomatoes and canned 
sardines to eat 
children at the transit camp who now number in the thousands 
are suffering heat exhaustion and diarrhea another 14000 refugees 
wait in similar conditions at the adjacent camp of azraq ii while 
thousands more have been placed in camps in amman 
refugees surrounded a van as it was leaving the azraq i camp 
pulling out the nine people who were on their way to amman airport 
for the trip home according to witnesses 
the eight men and one elderly woman on the bus were named 
gujral the same as indias foreign minister kumar gujral and the 
refugees mistakenly thought they were relatives being given 
preferential treatment said dr ak amrohi first secretary at 
the indian embassy in amman 
people complain of bureaucratic bungling insufficient food and 
water and cramped conditions that make sleep impossible and the 
spread of contagious diseases increasingly likely 
