polands finance minister said thursday the 
effects of the persian gulf crisis combined with failure to ease 
the massive polish debt were endangering his countrys attempt to 
turn capitalist 
the loss of revenue from business contracts with iraq and 
kuwait in addition to the rising price of oil will cost poland 2 
billion over the coming year said leszek balcerowicz 
poland has been very severely hit at a very delicate time 
of the reform program he told reporters 
iraq had been selling oil to poland at cutrate prices in return 
for a writeoff of an estimated 600 million debt incurred during 
the eightyear iraniraq war poland also sold iraq large 
quantities of weapons and polish companies were engaged in 
construction projects for iraqs postwar rehabilitation officials 
said 
the aug 2 invasion of kuwait has stopped all that and sent 
some 1000 polish workers home 
the crash reform program initiated jan 1 by polands first 
noncommunist government is designed to turn the centralized 
economy into a marketdriven capitalist system government 
subsidies to businesses have been cut off raising prices sharply 
and forcing enterprises to become competitive or go bankrupt 
resulting layoffs have driven unemployment to 5 percent a level 
unknown under the communist party which ruled poland until last 
year 
balcerowicz who also serves as deputy prime minister said 
polands top priority was to trim its 40billion debt twothirds 
of which is owed to other governments and the rest to banks 
how can we convince people theres a light at the end of the 
tunnel with the growing debt overhang he said 
but four days of talks with finance officials and bankers 
gathered here for the annual meeting of the world bank and 
international monetary fund he said had failed to yield concrete 
results 
there was considerable progress in understanding but a lack 
of readiness to act he said time is crucial 
poland is also facing the problem of having to pay with hard 
currency for much of its imports once its main trading partner the 
soviet union goes to a cashonly trade system based on realistic 
market values starting jan 1 
balcerowicz said poland was negotiating with the soviets to 
ensure there is no disruption in the gas pipeline supplies the 
soviets have told poland they will cut the supply from 82 billion 
cubic meters to 52 billion 
but balcerowicz said he views this as an opening position in 
negotiations we are insisting on maintaining the supply he 
said 
