<TEXT>
reporters who cover events that lead to 
civil lawsuits cant be jailed for refusing to provide notes 
photographs or news sources to parties in the suits the state 
supreme court ruled thursday 
the unanimous decision said a shield law added to the california 
constitution by voters in 1980 protects reporters from being held 
in contempt of court for withholding confidential sources notes or 
unpublished material 
the court ruled in may that the law can be breached in a 
criminal case requiring a reporter to provide evidence necessary 
to protect a defendants constitutional right to a fair trial but 
the justices said thursday that parties in a civil case have no 
similar constitutional right 
this is a complete victory for the journalists and the 
public said c michael cooney lawyer for the new york times 
co publisher of the santa barbara newspress 
the ruling was prompted by a lawsuit involving newspress 
photographer robert ponce 
the photographer took pictures of an auto accident on a us 101 
ramp in june 1984 two of which appeared in the newspaper 
volkswagen of america sued by an injured passenger sought ponces 
unpublished photos as evidence 
santa barbara county superior court judge patrick mcmahon 
ordered the newspaper to release the photos saying they showed 
public events and were not confidential the 2nd district court of 
appeal overturned his ruling and was upheld by the state supreme 
court 
