<TEXT>
regulators learned thursday the government 
fund protecting bank accounts is dwindling faster than thought only 
two months ago and they voted a 1991 increase of more than 60 
percent on the deposit insurance premiums charged banks 
the federal deposit insurance corps bank fund dropped from 
132 billion at the end of last year to 114 billion at the end 
of june a 14 percent decline 
fdic chairman l william seidman said he now expects that by the 
end of the year the fund will have lost closer to 3 billion 
rather than the 2 billion he earlier predicted 
this is the result of an increased number of institutions 
being likely to fail and continued erosion in real estate 
markets seidman told members of a house panel in a meeting which 
followed the fdic vote to boost premiums 
if continuing bank failures were to exhaust the insurance fund 
congress and the bush administration would have to consider a 
taxpayer bailout as they have with the sampl insurance fund 
after receiving the new financial report the fivemember fdic 
board raised the insurance premium charged banks by more than 60 
percent 
banks in 1991 will pay 195 cents for every 100 in deposits up 
from 12 cents this year and 83 cents last year the higher rate 
will raise the funds premium income from 28 billion in 1990 to 
48 billion in 1991 
under last years sampl bailout law the premium had been 
scheduled to rise to 15 cents regulators began considering an 
added emergency increase after seidman told senators in july that 
the bank fund likely would suffer its third consecutive loss 
in midaugust they proposed the maximum increase allowed by law 
to 195 cents by comparison savings institutions pay a 23cent 
premium 
the bank funds 184 billion loss in the first six months of 
1990 has reduced the level of reserves in the fund to only 60 cents 
for every 100 of insured deposits the minimum considered safe is 
125 per 100 at the end of 1987 the level was 110 
sixty cents is the lowest point in the funds history and the 
congressional general accounting office has warned that if the 
economy dips into a recession the fund could be wiped out 
banks have a variety of options for absorbing higher premiums 
including charging savers higher fees and paying them less 
interest charging borrowers more for loans reducing dividends to 
stockholders or cutting payroll and other expenses 
undoubtedly some part of it will be passed along to bank 
customers but certainly all of it wont be passed along 
seidman told the house banking subcommittee on financial 
institutions 
the agencys staff calculated that if all of the difference 
between the 195cent assessment and the previously scheduled 
15cent assessment were passed to depositors the annual return on 
a 10000 deposit would decline by 450 
if the 195cent rate had been in effect last year instead of 
the 83cent rate and banks absorbed all of it 69 additional banks 
would have recorded losses instead of a profit and four more banks 
would have failed 
administrationbacked legislation that passed the house last 
week and is pending in the senate would give the fdic power to 
raise premiums as high as it decided was necessary 
if the legislation passes before congress adjourns next month 
seidman said his board would consider further premium increases 
with a 195cent premium the fund would not reach the minimum safe 
level until after 1995 he told the house panel 
however he warned that at some point forcing banks to pay more 
becomes counterproductive by weakening the industry 
rep frank annunzio dill has proposed assessing banks a 
onetime charge of 1 for every 100 in deposits raising 25 
billion for the insurance fund they would be expected to replenish 
the money as it is spent 
that seidman warned could drive 28 banks into insolvency and 
push 241 banks below minimum capital requirement 
rep jim leach riowa said regulators should force banks to 
raise more capital from investors or retain earnings as a buffer 
against losses regulators should threaten to remove senior bank 
management unless they raise capital he said 
one has to be a logical nincompoop to think that more premiums 
are a preferable route more premiums make the system weaker more 
capital makes the system stronger he said 
</TEXT>
