a navy submarine recovered part of the cargo 
door that broke away from a united jetliner over the pacific last 
year sweeping nine people to their death authorities said 
thursday 
the crew of a deepsea submarine retrieved the lower half of the 
hatch from the ocean floor and located what is believed to be the 
doors upper half a navy spokeswoman said 
united airlines flight 811 had just taken off from honolulu 
international airport when the door and a large chunk of fuselage 
tore away at 22000 feet 
the piece was found late wednesday in 14100 feet of water 90 
miles southsouthwest of here said lt cmdr sandy stairs a 
spokeswoman for the us pacific fleet 
the 31foot submarine sea cliff videotaped the 6by10foot 
piece on the ocean floor and brought it to the surface with its 
hydraulic jaws stairs said it was brought onto the deck of the 
navy vessel the laney choust at about midnight wednesday 
during the 18hour dive wednesday the submarines threeman 
crew believed it also found the upper half of the cargo door about 
200 yards away from where the lower half was found stairs said the 
submarine planned to dive again thursday night to examine the 
debris which was spotted as a strong sonar contact 
the national transportation safety board called for the search 
in hopes that examining the door will lead to better aviation 
safety rules 
in washington the safety board said a preliminary examination 
by one of its investigators showed the door had fractured 
longitudinally near the midspan latch the eight sectors of the 
latch lock were all in the locked position and were deformed 
after investigators examine the recovered debris parts of it 
will be sent to the boeing co in seattle for a more detailed 
review under board direction ntsb officials said 
if the submarine is able to retrieve the top half of the door 
the sea cliff and its support ship are expected to return to pearl 
harbor late friday or early saturday 
the jumbo jet carried 355 passengers when it took off for new 
zealand on feb 24 1989 
shortly after takeoff the cargo door opened at 22000 feet 
nine passengers were swept out of the plane and five others 
suffered serious injuries the crew managed to return the jet to 
honolulu 
the ntsb inquiry determined that faulty design of a locking 
mechanism probably caused a cockpit light to falsely indicate the 
door was locked 
the agency blamed united boeing and the federal aviation 
administration for failing to correct problems with the door 
debris from the jet was located in july by a sonarscanning sled 
that can spot metallic objects over wide areas 
