<TEXT>
two infertility clinics charged by the federal 
trade commission with misrepresenting success rates have agreed not 
to make such claims in the future the ftc announced thursday 
one of the clinics ivf australia one of the largest providers 
of fertility services in the united states said its claims were 
not inaccurate but may have been hard to understand 
we have always provided the public with accurate 
information said vicki baldwin a founding director of the firm 
in a news release issued from its headquarters in greenwich conn 
we do agree that some prospective patients may have found our 
success rate reports difficult to interpret ms baldwin said 
thus in cooperation with the federal trade commission we have 
revised our materials to improve clarity 
the cases involve in vitro fertilization ivf services in 
which the sperm and the egg are joined together in the laboratory 
instead of naturally in the womb of the mother 
ivf australia offers medical services at united hospital port 
chester ny waltham weston hospital and medical center in 
waltham mass and at a clinic in mineola ny 
the other clinic involved is the west boca medical center in 
boca raton fla 
sid tyler executive vice president of nme hospital group in 
santa monica calif operator of the florida clinic said we 
dont agree completely with the ftc on this but nonetheless we 
have agreed with the consent order and we are certainly going to 
comply with the request that they have made that any statistical 
comparisons or statistical claims that we make are done 
comparably to similar national data so that we are talking about 
apples and apples 
the ftc invited public comment on the consent agreements with 
the clinics and noted that the allegations do not concern the 
quality of the services provided 
these two cases will provide important guidance to a growing 
industry about the support necessary to make valid success rate 
claims gloria cordes larson deputy director of the commissions 
bureau of consumer protection said 
the commission said infertility affects one in six us couples 
ivf australia advertised in newspapers and magazines that more 
than 28 percent of the couples who complete a cycle of treatment 
are becoming pregnant and that one out of three couples who 
complete a cycle of treatment is becoming pregnant 
a brochure sent to prospective patients said our experience 
indicates that when a patient at an ivf australia program completes 
four ivf treatment cycles the chance of giving birth is about 50 
percent 
the ftc said these claims misled consumers by overstating the 
likelihood of achieving either a live birth or a pregnancy it said 
a significant number of unsuccessful outcomes were excluded from 
the calculation used to determine success 
the consent order requires ivf australia to include in its 
calculations all patients who begin the program 
the complaint against the boca raton clinic charges that it 
advertised in local newspapers and national magazines that four 
of our first 12 patients participating in our in vitro 
fertilization program have achieved pregnancy and that our 
success rate is an impressive 30 percent well above the national 
average 
it said these determinations were based entirely on a chemical 
test which should have been subjected to confirmation by an 
ultrasound or sonogram test and was not 
the commission said its order provided that in making future 
claims the clinic must use the same tests that the other success 
rates use 
the agreement are open for public comment for 60 days after 
which the commission will decide whether to make them final 
final consent orders do not involve admission of a law violation 
but carry the force of law with respect to future actions each 
violation of such an order may result in a civil penalty of up to 
10000 
</TEXT>
