<TEXT>
the lower house of parliament on thursday 
overwhelmingly approved constitutional changes and a law that could 
result in a presidential election as early as nov 25 
the election law passed 26812 authorizes the speaker of 
parliament to set a date for elections as quickly as 60 days a 
second round of elections is possible if no candidate gets 50 
percent of the ballots in the first round 
under the constitutional amendment approved 3254 the 
president is elected in a general ballot and may serve up to two 
fiveyear terms 
the parliament banned campaign financing from foreign sources 
and campaigning 36 hours before the election deputies refused a 
proposal to bar campaigning at churches and other religious sites 
a common activity in poland 
the changes require approval by the upper chamber senate and 
the president but that is considered likely the senate is in 
session friday 
solidarity leader lech walesa has already declared his candidacy 
in the first popular presidential ballot since before world war ii 
he seeks to succeed gen wojciech jaruzelski who is stepping down 
early as head of state 
prime minister tadeusz mazowiecki a former adviser and ally of 
walesa also is considering running and is expected to announce his 
decision next week several other candidates are likely a 
candidate must be nominated by a party or else collect 100000 
signatures to get on the ballot 
a caucus representing former communists tried unsuccessfully to 
lower the number of signatures required to 50000 
jaruzelski asked parliament on sept 19 to shorten his term of 
office in order to permit an election in recent months there were 
increasing calls for the former communist party leader to step down 
as an unwanted symbol of the countrys old hardline order 
