<TEXT>
 
yesterday he had been happy but this sorrow descending upon 
him as it had the night before seemed to have confounded him 
beyond all hope since for the first time in his life he was 
unable to cut his trouble adrift to shed it like some startling 
and unwelcome chrysalis lie down in darkness 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
late afternoon william styron looks tired 
slouched in a chair in his hotel room his tie and jacket lying on 
the bed the air is hot and musty and the curtains are almost 
completely drawn blocking out the sun of a crisp september day 
the author is making a twoday trip to new york to promote 
darkness visible a memoir of madness a brief chronicle of his 
nearsuicidal bout with depression and eventual recovery 
the night before he appeared in a packed manhattan auditorium 
at the 92nd st y poetry center reading one passage from his new 
book and another from a novel in progress he seemed comfortable 
discussing his problems and expressed delight that his book had 
temporarily knocked donald trumps latest opus from the top of 
bestseller lists the audience responded enthusiastically 
but styron was also anxious to finish agreeing to a mere five 
to six minutes of questions and checking his watch to make sure 
that limit was not broken 
at his hotel room the author is again checking his watch he 
seems edgy distracted noting periodically he has to leave the 
hotel at 515 pm sharp that evening vanity fair is holding a 
reception in his honor at the century club his original article on 
depression had first appeared in the magazine 
 
i barely realized it but i was in a deep crisis i actually 
had ached so intensely over this wicked this monstrous 
disappoinment this betrayal that a kind of quivering st 
vitus dance had begun to possess my limbs i was suffering 
from an anxiety attack which each one of my psychic monitors had 
begun to regard gravely flashing alerts all through my flesh 
sophies choice 
 
darkness visible begins with a trip to paris in the fall of 
1985 when styron realized his emotional difficulties of the past 
several months might have a fatal outcome 
he soon broke down completely unable to sleep or drive or write 
and barely capable of speaking alcohol nauseated him in the book 
he admits to a history of heavy drinking and at the reading he said 
he still enjoys a glass of wine and the author was seized by 
uncontrollable fits of anxiety 
antidepressant medication prescribed by a psychiatrist only 
worsened his condition by early december he was ready to kill 
himself he couldnt even write a suicide note but drew upon 
some last gleam of sanity and checked into a hospital instead 
recuperating after a sevenweek stay 
i havent had any real afteraffects for a long long time 
styron insisted during the interview its over ive tried to 
make a point about it once its over its over once people get 
well theyre restored to the way they were before 
other writers have suffered from depression including f scott 
fitzgerald and sylvia plath leo tolstoys midlife crisis led him 
to become a devout christian philip roth writes about his problems 
in zuckerman unbound and the counterlife and camus novel 
the fall is a monologue by a depressed lawyer 
william james in the varieties of religious experience says 
it is a positive and active anguish a sort of physical neuralgia 
wholly unknown to normal life 
styron 65 could easily pass for a senator or a head of state 
he is stocky and broadshouldered with a wide forehead jowls 
nearly white hair and narrow eyes pinched at the edges his speech 
is fluid polished the vowels clipped the timbre rich 
he is a man who likes to get things finished done with a 
native of newport news va he knew in his late teens he wanted to 
be a writer and was impatient to get his first book published 
that came in 1951 with lie down in darkness a sprawling 
novel influenced by william faulkner and centered ironically on a 
young womans suicide 
styron has since become one of the most honored writers of the 
past 40 years winner in 1967 of the pulitzer prize for the 
confessions of nat turner and the american book award in 1979 for 
sophies choice which included a double suicide 
but there has also been this nagging sense of unfinished 
business it started at age 13 the author said with the death of 
his mother he became a hell raiser as a child admitting now 
he should have properly expressed his grief allowed it to work its 
way through his system 
if there were any guilty feelings about his mother styron did 
have a chance to make amends at an early age he served as a 
lieutenant in the marines during world war ii and in 1945 was 
stationed in okinawa he was to take part in the invasion of japan 
and didnt expect to come out alive 
the invasion never occurred the united states dropped the atom 
bomb instead 
some of my problems i think came from a continuing anguish 
over my mothers death and if i had gotten shot it would have been 
i suppose some kind of completion its hard to say how that would 
have worked out said styron who lives in connecticut with his 
wife they have four children 
when i was a young marine platoon leader there was this 
incredible sense of fate the myth at that age is youre going to 
live forever well i never believed that and my friends didnt i 
thought i was going to die 
styron insists go with the flow is now his philosophy the 
world will roll merrily on without me if i stop writing he says 
there are regrets about not having written richard iii but the 
author still looks back on a respectable body of work and 
considers darkness visible a fitting way to put his troubles 
behind him 
one thing you do learn is that youre really at the whim of 
forces beyond your control he said most people think mental 
health is something theyre invulnerable to they go through life 
thinking its something that happens to other people 
when the interview ends styron puts on his jacket moves over 
to the bed and sits for his picture to be taken his wrist turning 
for another look at the watch its 505 pm 
he doesnt shake hands but shyly lowers his face and mumbles 
goodbye perhaps thinking about the evening ahead or simply 
looking forward to finishing this trip and going home 
 
the grief is coming now she said to herself hes beginning 
to know what suffering is perhaps thats good for a man 
finally to know what suffering is to know what a woman somehow 
knows from the day she was born william styron lie down in 
darkness 
 
