professionals 
in the 20 years since theyve lost four out of five 
presidential elections thats not all due to the system as brown 
said there are a lot of reasons that are not related to the 
process at all 
but it hasnt helped 
before reform the presidntial primaries were a testing ground 
in which presidential candidates would try to show their strength 
far from home to show party leaders and delegates that they could 
be november winners now the primaries are the arena in which 
nominees are chosen there were 36 of them in 1988 
that preliminary competition tends to force candidates toward 
the left and to lock them into positions that can be liabilities 
in the final campaign for the white house 
democratic rules also tend to keep candidates in the race 
because nominating delegates must be assigned in proportion to 
primary election showings losers get their weekly share and an 
early decision on the nominee is almost impossible to gain 
what id like to do is get a consensus candidate early in 
the process and start running against george bush rather than 
against each other brown said 
brown said he doesnt want to go back to the smokefilled room 
but he does want pragmatic commonsense politics 
those have not been democratic hallmarks they werent showing 
in atlanta in 1988 when the winner michael dukakis agreed to 
rules concessions for 1992 in order to gain the backing of the 
loser jackson 
brown as jacksons convention manager helped fashion that 
unity pact brown as party chairman has changed much of it 
the democrats had set aside a bloc of convention seats and 
therefore nominating votes for elected officials and party 
leaders free of commitments to any candidate that reserved some 
muscle for the old guard at jacksons behest the number of 
uncommitted superdelegates was to have been cut next time he 
wanted more power in the primaries and he also wanted something 
close to pure proportional representation without the requirement 
that a candidate get 15 percent of a states votes to win any of 
its delegates 
a year ago the democratic national committee voted to seat a 
full roster of 303 superdelegates at the 1992 convention and 
reinforced the 15 percent threshold for candidates to gain primary 
election delegates meeting this month the committee added another 
80 appointed delegates for 1992 
thats been done without controversy the steps brown now 
envisions are an invitation to controversy and he knows it people 
who think they ought to be president are not inclined to leave the 
field quietly because party leaders tell them to or suggest to 
their supporters and donors that its time to quit theyre more 
likely to start protesting that kingmakers and bosses are trying to 
force them out 
you would have to do it very carefully brown said we 
still have a caucus and primary system where the voters are the 
final arbiters this is not going to be a hamhanded approach 
 
editors note walter r mears vice president and columnist 
for the associated press has reported on washington and national 
politics for more than 25 years 
