<TEXT>
ramesh jain is building a computer 
database so complicated it might seem like childs play 
the university of michigan researcher says his work is too early 
in development to predict its success but it will debunk the myth 
that a computer database has to consist of words or numbers 
how about pictures 
most existing computers recognize only keyboard symbols not 
images that are scanned into their memory 
the computer we are designing will do that jain said you 
can ask questions about pictures using pictures its just the 
research of a new area all the databases are not in terms of names 
or numbers theyre in shapes 
jain director of the schools artificial intelligence lab said 
the program could eventually be used in classrooms police labs 
real estate offices and museum warehouses 
in class for example students could use databases to identify 
leaves in botany education a tree leaf they couldnt identify 
could likely be matched by the computer comparing it to shapes 
colors sizes and textures in its memory 
karen brady an artist in the schools multimedia lab is using 
a sample database with pictures of oriental rugs a computer 
scanner copies the image of each rug into the computers memory 
the computer is programmed to recognize rug features including 
overall design patterns of the main and minor borders and color 
schemes sample rugs can be identified by the computer by matching 
them with such features in its memory 
the amount of information requires huge amounts of computer 
memory jain said he is starting the project on apple macintoshes 
but expects to graduate to larger systems 
some existing databases are based on images but none works 
directly with the pictures jain said 
at the michigan state police crime laboratory in east lansing 
unidentified fingerprints from crime scenes can be matched to 
suspects through images in police files 
but the program does not exclusively work with the images said 
robert slick a latent fingerprint examiner at the lab instead 
the computer assigns numerical values to characteristics of the 
fingerprint and searches the values in its memory for a match 
depending on the level of technology hes using it could be 
used in other areas as well slick said i would think that it 
could even be used in the identification of people thats pure 
speculation but the skys the limit in technology 
jim blackaby acting executive director of the museum computer 
network in syracuse ny says image storage is important to 
museums because it saves wear and tear on collections 
by having images on file researchers can call them up on the 
screen instead of pulling them out of storage 
while copies of paintings and sculptures already are filed on 
computers they cannot be retrieved by specifying an image without 
the key word that describes it blackaby said 
