<TEXT>
alzheimers victims who suffer behavioral 
problems such as paranoia and hallucinations tend to live about two 
years less than those who do not according to a published report 
a shortened lifespan also was associated with hearing loss and a 
later onset of the disease the university of washington 
researchers reported in the annals of internal medicine 
the study confirmed earlier findings that wandering and falling 
a common problem among alzheimers patients reduces lives by about 
three years 
the report suggests that we should try to improve the quality 
of survival and prevent the excess of disability said the 
studys author dr eric larson 
alzheimers progressively strips a persons ability to deal with 
and understand events and people complete household chores and 
even take care of oneself no cause or cure is known 
according to a recent report by congress office of technology 
assessment about 18 million americans have alzheimers so severe 
that others must care for them constantly an additional 1 million 
to 5 million have mild or moderate dementia 
patients live an average of five to eight years after being 
diagnosed with alzheimers according to the researchers 
the study followed 126 alzheimers patients in their late 70s 
for at least six years several factors including depression use 
of prescription drugs loss of appetite and restlessness did not 
affect the patients survival the study showed 
the scientists said they hope their work will be used to develop 
accurate forecasts of the diseases course 
creighton phelps of the alzheimers disease and related 
disorders association in chicago said the group planned to 
disseminate the study to its chapters 
this information linking behavioral problems to shorter 
survival is something we didnt know before he said 
