<TEXT>
lessons learned in the 1973 arab oil embargo have 
helped japan weather the gulf crisis even though danger lurks in 
the form of plummeting stock prices and rising interest rates 
nearly two months after iraq invaded kuwait gasoline prices are 
up only slightly in japan and there is little sign of the grave 
concern that might be expected from a country that relies on the 
middle east for 70 percent of its oil 
thats largely a result of the governments efforts to avoid a 
repeat of 1973 when japans economy was thrown into chaos through 
arab restrictions of oil exports and imports that tripled in price 
within months 
at the time the oil shock sent inflation spiraling and led 
to the first decline in japans gross national product during the 
postwar era 
japanese recall how they rushed to stores to buy toilet paper 
kerosene and other commodities amid fears of shortages the crisis 
atmosphere was heightened by emergency conservation measures that 
pulled the plug on neon lighting and closed gasoline stations on 
holidays and sundays 
but there have been no such scenes this time around 
the major reason is that the government has a deliberate 
policy of not causing panic said gregory clark a professor at 
sophia university specializing in the japanese economy that policy 
is aimed at dampening expectations of inflation 
japanese ministries have kept a close eye on companies plans to 
raise fuel prices to the consumer oil wholesalers have raised 
prices only once during the crisis and only after the government 
demanded they narrow the increase 
meanwhile the powerful ministry of international trade and 
industry on tuesday asked wholesalers of liquefied petroleum gas to 
absorb higher costs by streamlining operations and limiting price 
increases to the minimum the kyodo news service reported 
japan is also less vulnerable to another oil shock because 
it has reduced its dependence on foreign oil for its overall energy 
needs from about 75 percent to under 60 percent according to a 
western energy analyst 
for further protection the country has built up a 144day 
reserve of oil japan also has been purchasing additional supplies 
from saudi arabia and iran since the international embargo on iraq 
and kuwait began in early august 
so far we have enough supply and enough stock to cover the 
loss so i dont think we have serious problems in the short run 
said hideki matsumoto a senior economist at the private institute 
of energy economics japan 
he said the government may draw from that stockpile in winter 
when demand for petroleum products increases 
in the longer term however continuing uncertainty in the gulf 
and sharply increased oil prices pose threats to the worlds no 2 
economy so strong that it has grown each month for nearly four 
years 
the stock market which was already bearish has slid 28 percent 
since the aug 2 invasion of kuwait on wednesday the 225share 
nikkei stock average dropped 475 percent to end the day at 
2225062 its lowest closing level since jan 5 1988 
japanese commercial banks with their large share portfolios 
have been hit particularly hard the reduced value of those assets 
rendered some banks unable to meet international reserve 
requirements that become mandatory in two years analysts say this 
could lead to reduced lending overseas 
economists are particularly worried about accelerated interest 
rate growth and inflationary pressure since the crisis began 
retail costs of petroleum products are likely to increase in 
larger and more frequent increments if the crisis persists the 
real blow will be the price hike of petroleumrelated products 
which will surface before the end of the year predicted josen 
takahashi chief economist at the mitsubishi research institute 
perhaps most ominous is the possible effect of rising interest 
rates on the expensive japanese realestate market 
although japan is only 4 percent the size of the united states 
its real estate is estimated at nearly four times the total value 
of us real estate about 15 trillion land prices climbed 13 
percent in the 12 months ending in july according to one government 
survey 
some analysts believe the interest rate increases could force 
land speculators to sell their holdings and burst the real estate 
bubble 
a collapse of the real estate market said clark would have 
staggering effects on this economy and could lead to a lengthy 
recession 
so far said clark the government has done well to avert the 
inflationary scare of the 1973 oil shock 
what they cant control is the period over which interest 
rates remain high he added and this is whats going to make 
or break this economy 
