<TEXT>
here are excerpts from a prosecution memorandum 
to us district judge kimba m wood outlining the governments 
full case against michael milken and urging the judge to severely 
sentence him 
the documents were made public wednesday by order of the judge 
a day after the defense released its own presentencing memorandum 
urging leniency the documents were edited to conceal identities of 
milken associates who are labeled as john doe 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
milkens crimes formed a pattern of calculated fraud deceit and 
corruption of the highest magnitude in a highly sophisticated and 
systematic way milken endeavored to enhance his power and enlarge 
his wealth by willingly cheating clients manipulating the 
marketsand evading the laws and rules designed to safeguard the 
investing public 
milken developed and nurtured corrupt relationships with 
numerous clients and customers including ivan f boesky the 
prominent wall street arbitrageur and john doe an institutional 
money manager together with these criminal associates milken 
harnessed the vast economic power of drexel burnham lamberts 
highyield department and directed it to enhance his power and 
increase his wealth the highyield department became the means 
through which milken rewarded his friends defeated his rivals and 
committed his crimes 
contrary to milkens persistent efforts to minimize the 
nature and scope of his criminal conduct the six charges to which 
milken pleaded guilty provide but a sampling of the larger pattern 
of criminal activity that permeated milkens operation of the 
highyield department 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
in our view three primary reasons mandate that milken be 
severely punished for his crimes first milkens criminal conduct 
as reflected by his guilty plea was sweeping it warrants the 
imposition of a substantial term of imprisonment 
second notwithstanding his entry of a guilty pea milken has 
scarcely accepted responsibility for his crimes he has done little 
to mitigate his punishment 
finally milkens sentence will be used in criminal courts 
throughout this country as the model for how our justice system 
should treat whitecollar criminals this courts message must be a 
clarion call to the community that financial crime cannot be 
countenanced and will not be tolerated 
put simply milkens crimes were crimes of greed 
arrogance and betrayal 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
poised atop the drexel financial colossus milken routinely 
possessed more power and better information than his clients 
customers and the market 
on certain occasions milken engendered the loyalty of his 
customers by abetting their crimes and violations on other 
occasions milken unlawfully provided gratuities often in the 
form of valuable investment opportunities available only to those 
designated by him to personally enrich institutional fiduciaries 
in order to influence them to direct their institutional business 
to drexel the net result of these corrupt practices was the 
creation of a marketplace rife with conflicts of interest and 
manipulative conduct 
contrary to his efforts to characterize the crimes he 
committed as petty milkens crimes were neither technical nor 
victimless they included the fraudulent misappropriation of funds 
from unsophisticated investors who entrusted their funds to the 
management of others the deception of market participants who 
acted in reliance on the integrity of the marketplace and contempt 
for the legal framework designed to protect such investors and 
ensure the integrity of the market 
milkens criminal conduct was calculated and systematic 
rather than gratuitous and aberrational and milkens criminal 
activity was a significant and necessary component of the growth of 
his power in the highyield market 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
milken merits scant credit for accepting responsibility and no 
credit for cooperation milkens decision reflects surrender 
not contrition further milken has not accepted responsibility for 
all of his crimes indeed his selfserving rationalizations to the 
probation department undercut any serious claim that he has truly 
accepted responsiblity for even the crimes to which he has now 
pleaded finally in spite of his many postinvestigation social 
and charitable good works milken has not taken and has indicated 
that he will not take affirmative steps to clean up the industry 
he dirtied 
milken should be punished as the unreconstructed and 
unapologetic man that he is 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
having been responsible for drexels rise to prominence drexel 
might have been milkens to destroy but there is no question that 
the excesses in drexels corporate culture that milken fathered 
hastened the collapse of the company corrupted many young 
professionals and occasioned the loss of thousands of jobs were it 
not for the lawlessness of milkens highyield department there 
would not have been grand jury and sec securities and exchange 
commission investigations even after the investigations 
moreover the greedy habits of the milken years led to the payment 
of tens of millions of dollars in 1989 bonuses and compensation as 
drexel spiraled towards bankruptcy had more money been kept in 
drexel rather than paid out to milken and other members of the 
highyeild department drexel undoubtedly would have had a greater 
chance to survive 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the absurdity of milkens claimed disinterest in wealth is 
demonstrated by his direct compensation from drexel and his 
indirect compensation through drexel milkens compensation from 
drexel represented an enormous percentage of drexels bottom line 
a footnote showed the escalation of his compensation to 550 
million in 1986 or 458 percent of drexels operating profit his 
compensation of 316 million in 1987 was estimated at 817 percent 
of the companys operating profit according to the government 
as one former employee put it milken never let go of a 
nickel except to get a better grip 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
between 1983 and march 1986 drexel raised over 800 million for 
the boesky organization through the sale of highyield securities 
these financings culminated in march 1986 when drexel and milken 
raised 660 million for the boesky organization 
this mutually beneficial relationship between boesky and milken 
evolved over time into a corrupt one in which each engaged in 
unlawful conduct to benefit the other the secret boesky 
relationship also allowed milken to invest in lucrative trading 
opportunities which he was legally barred from because of drexels 
involvement in certain corporate finance transactions 
in may 1986 dennis levine a prominent merger and 
acquisition specialist then employed by drexel was arrested for 
insider trading the levine arrest struck a weighty blow in the 
investment community more particularly it was an ominous event 
for boesky because of his own illegal dealings with levine and 
for milken because the arrest signaled a greater law enforcement 
vigilance in the investment banking area following the 
levine arrest unlawful trading in the highyield department 
slowed 
more particularly the levine arrest affected the course of the 
unlawful milkenboesky relationship in july 1986 boesky visited 
milken for the purpose of discussing a range of business items 
both lawful and unlawful during the course of a poolside 
discussion between milken and boesky at milkens home the two 
discussed the effect of levines arrest on their unlawful dealings 
 
boesky and milken did not meet again until october 1986 
shortly after the announcement of boeskys plea and settlement with 
the government john doe asked milken if he had been careful 
in his october 1986 meeting with boesky milken answered that he 
thought he had been careful but that he was not entirely sure that 
he had been careful enough john does fears were justified 
the government taperecorded milkens meeting with boesky in a room 
at the beverly hills hotel 
</TEXT>
