<TEXT>
during the period form 1984 through 1986 drexel was at the 
center of wall streets takeover boom clients came to drexel for 
the most part because of drexels unmatched ability to raise 
capital through the sale of highyield securities 
there is substantial evidence that milken caused drexel to 
buy and sell securities based upon material nonpublic information 
misappropriated from certain drexel clients in one of these 
instances milken traded on insider information for his own 
account 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
milkens submission dramatically exposes the gulf between his 
crimes and his conviction on the one hand and his continuing 
agitprop on the other milken has been convicted of serious and 
sweeping crimes his good works however commendable should not 
shield him from incarceration he should be sentenced to a 
substantial term of imprisonment 
milken is selling an old and threadbare story by focusing 
the courts attention on the five specific crimes he had admitted 
and by wholly ignoring his conviction on a broad conspiracy charge 
milken is attempting to minimize his criminal conduct were 
milken to address the true range of his crimes however even he 
would have to acknowledge a different conclusion milkens crimes 
were serious and extensive 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
milken has been convicted of enormously serious crimes 
conspiracy to violate the laws of the united states securities 
fraud mail fraud wire fraud tax fraud and recordkeeping and 
reporting violations 
although he has limited his allocution to five separate 
acts in furtherance of that conspiracy this court can and should 
sentence milken for all of his crimes 
in united states v kittel kittel a member of the 
new york chapter of the hells angels motorcycle club was charged 
with conspiracy to manufacture and distribute large quantities of 
methamphetamine and with 11 substantive counts relating to the 
unlawful distribution of methamphetamine he was convicted on his 
plea of guilty to the conspiracy charge and to one of the 
distribution charges in kittels sentencing however the 
government alleged that kittel had participated in the murder and 
dismemberment of another hells angels club member and the unlawful 
manufacture of an explosive device among other acts of violence 
judge pierre leval sentenced kittel to a 14year term of 
imprisonment stating that the sentence was based not only the 
particular offenses to which kittel had pleaded guilty but on the 
governments evidence of kittels unadmitted crimes persistent 
drug dealing and acts of violence 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
moreover although the government is asking the court to 
sentence milken on crimes more numerous than he has specifically 
admitted these additional charges are similar to the crimes that 
milken has admitted manipulating stocks unlawfully influencing 
corporate events through the concealed ownership of securities 
unlawfully providing benefits to clients and client representatives 
in order to cultivate their business and fraudulently 
misappropriating funds from clients 
indeed milkens agreement to pay 200 million in criminal 
penalities and 400 million in restitution dramatically belies both 
his contention that he committed only the five enumerated crimes 
and his argument that even these crimes were aberrational and 
technical violations these fines penalties and restitution fix 
the scope of milkens criminal conduct milkens agreement to pay 
these monies stands out as the most reliable measure of his 
criminal conduct 
for all these reasons this case is sharply different from 
united states v freeman in freeman where the judge refused 
to admit a sentencing report on additional crimes the defendant 
pleaded guilty to one narrow insider trading charge not to 
multiple offenses and a broad conspiracy charge unlike milken 
robert freeman did not acknowledge the governments right to put 
before the court his unadmitted offenses unlike milken 
freeman in his allocution did not admit that he committed crimes 
additional to the crimes to which he specifically pleaded guilty 
finally freeman did not agree to pay criminal fines and 
restitution penalties of 600 million 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
milken should be sentenced to a substantial period of 
incarceration commensurate with his crimes those crimes were 
pervasive and systemic they were committed for venal reasons to 
enhance milkens personal power and increase his wealth no good 
works undertaken by milken mitigate the imperative of a substantial 
prison term milkens proposal that he be sentenced to a 
probationary term and community service is absurd such a sentence 
would eviscerate law enforcements efforts to police and deter 
financial crime 
milkens crimes have had nationwide impact and his 
sentence will become the touchstone for every sentence for 
financial crime in the country 
other sentences demonstrate a consensus among judges that 
absent significant actual cooperation a major securities law 
violator such as milken will receive a substantial term of 
incarceration 
boeskys threeyear term of incarceration provides a useful 
point of departure as an initial symbolic matter milken stands 
convicted of six times as many felony charges as boesky and has 
agreed to pay six times boeskys criminal fine and civil penalty 
while the government does not suggest that simple arithmetic should 
determine milkens sentence milkens suggestion that facing 
almost six times boeskys penalty he merits a fraction of his 
punishment is preposterous 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
like boesky and levine milken committed very serious crimes 
unike boesky and levine however milken has not cooperated on the 
urging of the government boesky and levine each received reduced 
sentences because of their extraordinary assistance in the 
successful prosecutions of others 
boeskys cooperation resulted directly and indirectly in 
the successful prosecution of numerous prominent securities 
industry professionals in addition to milken in sharp contrast 
during the four years of boeskys cooperation milken has 
vigorously contested the governments charges and allowed the 
