<TEXT>
two separate regulators for securities and 
futures markets may be too many as the links between wall street 
and chicago bind the markets together a congressional study has 
concluded 
a study of financial market technology by the congresss office 
of technology assessment suggested creating one regulatory agency 
with responsibility over securities including futures and options 
the report found that dual regulatory agencies may no longer 
be appropriate for what is now one marketplace 
the study scheduled to be made public today could heat up the 
simmering dispute between the rival regulators the securities and 
exchange commission and the commodity futures trading commission 
both agencies have engaged in a war of words over which should 
regulate stock index futures and their margins 
stock index futures are futures contracts that allow investors 
to bet on the movement of a whole series of stocks without having 
to buy the underlying securities margins are the downpayments paid 
by investors buying securities on credit securities margins are 
about 50 percent of the stocks value while futures margins are 
usually just 5 percent of the market value 
the 220page report electronic bulls and bears us 
securities markets and inforamtion technology was an outgrowth 
of the 1987 stock market crash 
the study looks at the regulatory structure and says hey 
these are now one market and having two agencies that fight each 
doesnt make any sense said vary t coates project director of 
the study the study also is critical of the specialist system of 
trading at the new york and american stock exchanges 
the ota does not make recommendations to congress but provides 
various policy options officials stressed the options included 
clearer definitions of jurisdiction by congress and setting up a 
multiagency panel with binding decisionmaking authority 
and the one that looks best is to integrate having one 
regulatory agency and this should be reexamined by the congress 
said ms coates commodities trading would be left in the hands of 
a separate regulator 
the report noted that the biggest stumbling block to a merger is 
different congressional committees have jurisdiction over the 
agencies and may not be willing or able to agree to consolidation 
of jurisdiction 
rep john dingell dmich chairman of the energy and commerce 
committee that oversees the sec said the panel would look at 
reforming the us regulatory structure which he called 
fragmented and uncoordinated and out of step with the way 
these new electronic bulls and bears run 
the reports finding bolstered a bill proposed earlier this year 
by reps dan glickman dkan and dennis eckart dohio for 
merging the sec and cftc into a unified super regulatory 
agency 
it is gratifying to know that an unbiased and careful analysis 
by an arm of congress has reached the same conclusion that the sec 
has been urging for some time said mary mccue an sec 
spokeswoman 
they have their own opinion its just not what we subscribe 
to said cftc spokesman david gary we feel the markets are 
linked but there is no need for one regulator in fact we remain 
firmly in the camp of functional regulation 
the report also said the sec and cftc often take radically 
different positions on issues and those differences raise 
doubts about the reliability of their coordination and cooperation 
during market emergencies 
earlier this year the heads of both agencies trashed each 
others study of the causes of the 1987 stock market crash 
accusing one another of selfserving interpretation of the same 
data 
in january a draft version of the report drew fire from a 
blueribbon advisory panel that included representatives from 
exchanges in new york and chicago for criticizing the specialist 
system as faltering and possibly irredeemably obsolete 
under the specialist system stock can only be traded through 
certain designated exchange members charged with maintaining an 
orderly market in that security even if it means buying or 
selling the stock because no other takers can be found 
critics claim specialists are unable to keep up with the massive 
volume that occurs in a market crisis like the 1987 crash but 
supporters say specialists stayed at their posts taking orders 
when other traders werent answering their phones during the crash 
while stock exchanges have sophisticated support systems on 
their trading floors they have resisted the use of electronic 
systems for afterhours and remotesite trading said the study 
which found recently announced plans for afterhours trading 
belated cautious and tighly limited 
the report also said the futures markets have resisted 
bringing technology into their domestic trading pits 
most futures exchanges still utilize the boisterous system of 
shouts and hand signals known as open outcry which makes it 
difficult to prevent fraud and assure investors they are getting 
the best price said the ota 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

