<TEXT>
flying is getting safer but more planes in 
the sky will mean more crashes unless the airline industry takes 
action a boeing co study says 
the study also indicates a few simple changes in operations plus 
some relatively inexpensive equipment might help reduce serious 
accidents earl weener boeing commercial airplane groups chief 
engineer for safety said wednesday 
the airplane manufacturer has kept statistics on all free world 
commercial jets for the past 30 years the company predicts the 
worldwide accident rate for jetliners should decline to about 1 per 
million flights in 2005 compared with an average of about 15 per 
million in the past 10 years 
but the number of jets is expected to double in the next 15 
years to about 13000 weener said actual aircraft losses can be 
expected to grow to 20 per year by 2005 up from a yearly average 
of 15 during the past decade 
that means a major air crash every 2 weeks or so something 
that wont sit well with the traveling public no matter how low the 
accident rate is weener said 
if the general public understood rates there wouldnt be a 
state lottery in existence weener said 
boeing which has 60 percent of the worlds commercial jet 
market has been pushing its study among air carriers industry 
groups and government regulators for the past year weener said 
weener who briefed a group of reporters on the study wednesday 
plans to make presentations to carriers and regulators next month 
in europe and southeast asia 
so far boeing has seen a great deal of understanding and 
interest on the part of airlines but its been difficult to 
determine what the results have been weener said this year there 
have been nine hull loss accidents wrecks in which the 
aircraft was destroyed or too badly damaged to fix which 
statistically would make 1990 one of the better years he said 
dave duff spokesman for the federal aviation administration in 
seattle said the agency is looking at the study but hasnt made 
any decisions on it 
the study says investigating agencies found that of the 121 
hullloss accidents in the past 10 years the flight crew was the 
primary cause in 88 accidents or 725 percent 
weener said boeing isnt holding pilots entirely to blame in 
most cases he said the flight crew was only the last party who 
could have prevented the accident in a chain of events boeing 
has used the data to help design aircraft that are more mistake 
tolerant he said 
a spokesman for the air line pilots association was not 
immediately available for comment wednesday but alpa officials 
previously have said they support boeings study 
the study focuses on what might be done to avoid crew error 
especially on takeoffs and landings where nearly 70 percent of 
hullloss accidents occur 
among its recommendations 
install ground proximity warning systems in all jets and 
make sure crews pay attention to them the systems which warn 
pilots to pull up when the ground gets too near have been required 
in us jetliners since 1975 but not in all foreign commercial 
jets 
install instrument landing systems for all runways and 
encourage pilots to use them even in good weather virtually all 
us airports have instrument landing systems but many have them 
on only one runway many foreign airports lack them altogether 
weener said 
make better use of flight data recorders the black boxes 
that monitor flights currently 12 carriers none of them in this 
country use the monitors to review flights and let pilots learn 
what they might have done better weener said airline managers 
have to see the monitors as teaching tools he added 
</TEXT>
