<TEXT>
in a new indication of the escalating economic 
fallout from the persian gulf turmoil the head of the world bank 
said today that he may be forced to call upon rich nations to boost 
their support for the international lending institution by early 
next year 
world bank president barber conable said that if oil prices 
remain at current high levels over the next three months his 
institution would not have enough in existing resources to cushion 
the shock on the world economy 
conables comments represented a change from his position just a 
few days ago at that time he and officials of the banks sister 
lending organization the international monetary fund insisted 
that they could handle the economic impact of the persian gulf 
crisis with available resources without tapping rich countries for 
additional funds 
however as delegates from 154 member countries of the two 
institutions were holding their annual meeting this week the price 
of oil jumped at one point to close to 40 
conable told reporters today that if oil prices stayed at high 
levels into 1991 he believed it would be necessary to ask for 
voluntary contributions from major industrial countries and oil 
producing nations that money would be used to make nointerest 
loans to countries especially hard hit by the rise in oil prices 
and other economic fallouts from the persian gulf turmoil 
if the price of oil stays up and there continues to be turmoil 
and uncertainty and an impact on the global economy clearly it 
will have a major impact on significant parts of the developing 
world conable said 
other officials of the world bank suggested that the proposed 
new lending facility would be available to work with the gulf 
crisis financial coordination group the steering committee of 
donor countries unveiled by president bush in his speech to the 
imfworld bank opening session on tuesday 
officials said that donations raised by the crisis group which 
is headed by treasury secretary nicholast brady might be funneled 
to this new lending facility for distribution to needy countries 
however they stressed that discussions on this matter remained at 
a preliminary stage 
both the imf and world bank had signaled earlier this week that 
they were ready to provide significant economic support to hardhit 
countries endorsing a request made by the bush administration but 
that approval involved the use of existing programs 
the crisis group with officials representing more than 20 
nations held an organizational session wednesday at the us 
treasury 
the united states had hoped to amass commitments this week for 
between 13 billion and 15 billion in aid to turkey jordan and 
egypt those frontline nations have been hard hit by the un 
economic sanctions placed on iraq after its aug 2 invasion of 
kuwait 
but some european nations objected that the figure was too high 
and that a more realistic amount was 9 billion with 6 billion of 
that support coming from oilrich mideast nations and 3 billion 
from the rest of the world 
following two hours of closeddoor discussions at the us 
treasury officials reported no resolution of the funding question 
also left unresolved were objections voiced to including jordan 
in the assistance package saudi arabia and kuwait have complained 
that jordan is showing reluctance to support the un trade embargo 
and therefore should not get aid 
and some nations raised the question of including other 
especially hardhit nations in the frontline category in addition 
to turkey jordan and egypt 
proponents of a longer list pointed to a new world bank study 
that identified bangladesh india pakistan the philippines sri 
lanka and sudan as seriously hurt by the persian gulf crisis 
us officials said they would not oppose expanding the list of 
most needy nations as long as the list did not grow too long 
one senior treasury official briefing reporters on condition of 
anonymity said many of the unresolved matters should be cleared up 
in discussions by lowerlevel working groups before the full crisis 
coordinating panel meets again on oct 12 
the nations participating with the united states in wednesdays 
meeting included japan west germany britain france canada 
italy saudi arabia kuwait the united arab emirates qatar and 
south korea 
in addition representatives of belgium the netherlands sweden 
and switzerland were added at the last minute after west germany 
and others argued that the list of potential donor countries needed 
to be expanded 
the us official said however that not all of the 
participating countries had made a commitment to provide financial 
assistance 
representatives from the 12nation european community and the 
gulf cooperation council of persian gulf countries also attended 
the meeting 
</TEXT>
