<DOCNO> AP900927-0226 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
italys first antimonopoly law cleared its last 
hurdle thursday 
the industry commission of the italian senate voted unanimously 
to approve the legislation which will bring italy into line with 
regulations laid down recently by the european community 
this decision has enabled us to provide an essential 
instrument to regulate the domestic market in harmony with the 
european community orms said senator robert cassola 
president of the senates industry commission 
the senate approved the law in a brief morning session adding 
no changes to the version already approved by the chamber of 
deputies 
italy was among the last of its european counterparts to pass an 
antitrust law 
the measure is designed to ensure free competition principles 
and prohibit the formation of monopolies or agreements among firms 
that would create dominant market positions 
the legislation isnt likely to have any immediate impact on the 
current concentration of italian industry however 
other than the state monopolies that have formed over the 
years there are very few monopolies in italy said paolo filippo 
lardera italy analyst with ubs phillips and drew in london 
this measure must be viewed in a wider european context 
because italian industry is already disadvantaged with respect to 
the rest of europe in terms of dimension and the fragmentation of 
many sectors lardera said 
under the law an antimonopoly commission will be established 
to enforce the new norms the commission will have authority to 
review cases on its own or on request by the industry ministry 
the most controversial portion of the new law regulates the 
relationship between banks and industry limiting the degree of 
control industrial companies can acquire over the financial sector 
as a result of the new law an industrialist wont be allowed to 
acquire direct or indirect shareholdings of more than 15 percent in 
a bank 
furthermore a company must inform the bank of italy if it takes 
up more than 5 percent of a bank companies will be permitted to 
participate in shareholder syndicates of banks provided they dont 
gain a majority position in the syndicate 
these provisions evolved in an effort championed by the bank of 
italy to safeguard the financial sector from manipulation by 
industrial companies 
although italys 1936 banking law prevents commercial banks from 
taking permanent shareholdings in industry until now there was no 
legislation to prevent companies from acquiring stakes in banks 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

