<TEXT>
a liquidation plan for american continental 
corp formerly led by charles h keating jr is headed toward a 
creditors committee after a nod from a federal judge 
the plans provisions include a 21 million payment by the 
government to creditors disposal of american continentals assets 
and agreement by the government to join lawsuits filed by creditors 
against keating and others 
during a hearing wednesday district judge richard bilby 
indicated he intends to approve the plan with some modifications 
law clerk linda mcnulty said thursday 
the plan now goes to a creditors committee which will revise 
it before returning it to the judge bilby could either approve it 
or order more changes as early as next week ms mcnulty said 
the plan would then be sent to all of the approximately 25000 
creditors both a majority of individual creditors and those 
holding the majority of the 365 million debt must approve the 
plan 
phoenixbased american continental filed for chapter 11 
bankruptcy protection in april 1989 the next day its primary 
subsidiary lincoln savings and loan association of irvine calif 
was seized by federal regulators 
in a related ruling wednesday bilby approved the settlement of 
two lawsuits filed by american continental investors both were 
against law firms accused of helping keating deceive investors and 
government regulatory agencies as to the stability of his financial 
empire 
the settlements for a total 243 million will return 10 
percent of what investors are believed to have lost when american 
continental collapsed 
keating and three other former executives of american 
continental or lincoln were indicted in los angeles last week on 
state charges of securities fraud stemming from the sales of junk 
bonds keating remained jailed thursday in lieu of 5 million bond 
pending an oct 5 arraignment although he has appealed to the 
state supreme court to reduce his bail 
the liquidation plan was agreed to by american continental its 
creditors and the resolution trust corp the federal agency that 
took over lincoln after it was seized by regulators 
under the plan american continentals remaining assets last 
valued at 16 million would be disposed of over a threeyear 
period 
the rtc would provide creditors with 21 million immediately 
upon approval of the plan providing creditors with compensation 
ranging up to 21 cents on the dollar 
in return the creditors would drop all claims against lincoln 
savings 11 subsidiaries 
the plan also calls for the rtc to become a party in a series of 
lawsuits against more than 50 defendants including keating other 
former american continental and lincoln officials and numerous 
business associates 
