its shops are recognizable by their dark green fronts and 
blackberry sprig motif and are bestknown for their flowerprint 
victorianstyle dresses 
in a drastic switch the company said it decided to largely 
abandon manufacturing its own apparel because it can be bought much 
more cheaply from outside suppliers 
the slimdown is part of a yearold costcutting program it 
said it blamed the strong british pound and high inflation for its 
woes 
seven of its nine factories in britain and ireland will be 
closed or sold and 1500 of its 8150 jobs will go the company 
said 
stock of laura ashley holdings has suffered along with the 
companys fortunes it traded at the equivalent of 112 a share on 
londons stock exchange thursday unchanged from wednesday and 
less than half the price at which investors snapped up the shares 
when the company went public in 1985 
moneylosing laura ashley is not the only troubled british 
retailer many operators have suffered from 15 percent interest 
rates engineered by the government to curb inflation by slowing 
consumer spending the annual inflation rate is running at 106 
percent 
another of britains onetime retailing stars the sock chain 
sock shop international plc fell into the hands of administrators 
earlier this year 
laura ashley said it will retain enough inhouse manufacturing 
to respond to changes in market needs it said it would continue 
printing its own fabrics and wallpaper and making its own 
curtains 
chairman bernard ashley issued a statement saying if laura 
ashley is to survive in todays highly competitive environment 
it could no longer supply its stores worldwide with garments made 
in its british factories 
for years the company had pursued a strategy of being a fully 
integrated retailer by making what it sold 
in late august laura ashley moved to raise cash and inspire 
confidence by selling a 15 percent stake to the japanese retailer 
jusco co for 56 million the ashley family with the ashley 
foundation retained a 59 percent stake 
joan dolier a retail analyst with the london investment firm 
county natwest woodmac said about the latest moves its good 
they have bitten the bullet longterm they had to bring down the 
cost base in order to have a viable continuing business 
brian corris an analyst with barclays de zoete wedd ltd said 
i think its got a long way to go but this abandoning 
manufacturing is obviously a step in the right direction 
mrs dolier blamed the companys difficulties on mismanagement 
it hasnt been a sale problem its been a cost problem she 
said 
the laura ashley look still has appeal mrs dolier said the 
biggest asset the company has is the laura ashley brand there is 
still a lot of goodwill attached to that 
the company which had been expected to report its halfyear 
results this week said they would be released in midoctober 
it lost the equivalent of about 183 million in the year ended 
jan 27 compared with a profit of 157 million the previous year 
sales grew to 555 million from 472 million 
the late laura ashley and her husband bernard began the clothier 
as a small cottage industry in a london apartment 37 years ago 
they printed fabrics on their kitchen table 
the couple expanded into garments accessories wallpaper and 
soft furnishings they opened their first store in 1968 
the welshborn mrs ashley died of head injuries in september 
1985 at the age of 60 after falling down steep stairs at her 
daughters west england home 
</TEXT>
