<TEXT>
a federal judge today put off the monday 
sentencing of michael milken and ordered an extraordinary hearing 
to consider the unadmitted crimes alleged by the government against 
the junkbond financier 
us district judge kimba m wood said she would hold a hearing 
in early october for approximately two weeks and give each side 20 
hours to present arguments before pronouncing sentence 
milken pleaded guilty in april to six felonies and faces a 
maximum 28 years in prison for his role in wall streets worst 
financial scandal 
the government had urged the judge to give milken a stiff 
sentence in a presentencing memorandum that outlined a broader 
array of crimes than those milken admitted in his plea bargain 
more than 200 pages of documents detailing those accusations 
were released wednesday by order of the judge 
the defense also had released a mountain of documents refuting 
the governments arguments and suggesting community service as an 
alternative sentence for the fallen billionaire 
federal law allows a judge to consider such evidence before 
passing sentence but must give the defense an opportunity to 
respond 
woods ruling shocked defense attorneys who have wanted to 
proceed wih the sentencing for months 
lead attorney arthur liman said i was hoping we could 
dispense with this 
he said such a hearing would prolong the extraordinary anguish 
and agony for my clients family 
wood tentatively scheduled a conference between the prosecutors 
and milkens lawyers tuesday to further define the extent of the 
extraordinary hearing it was unclear when milken would be 
ultimately sentenced 
milken was not in court 
your purpose should be to shed light on the defendants 
character wood told the opposing lawyers 
woods ruling made it almost certain that milkens chief accuser 
ivan boesky would be called to testify about the extent of his 
relationship with milken 
but lawyers said it was unclear whether milken would be present 
in the courtroom for such proceedings 
in their presentencing memorandum the prosecutors did not 
prescribe a specific sentence for milken but drew a comparison to 
his coconspirator boesky the convicted speculator and informant 
paid 100 million to settle insider trading charges pleaded guilty 
to a felony and was sentenced to a threeyear term now completed 
milken stands convicted of six times as many felony charges as 
boesky and has agreed to pay six times boeskys criminal fine and 
civil penalty the prosecution said 
while the government does not suggest that simple arithmetic 
should determine milkens sentence milkens suggestion that 
facing almost six times boeskys penalty he merits a fraction of 
his punishment is preposterous 
milken one of the nations richest men paid a record 600 
million in penalties as part of his plea agreement 
the governments memo which urged a substantial prison term for 
milken was riddled with allegations of insider trading 
manipulation bribery and hiding evidence by milken going far 
beyond the felonies to which he pleaded guilty but the document 
offered little in the way of new evidence to support the claims 
it also suggsted milkens alleged greed hastened the demise of 
his former employer the nowdefunct junkbond powerhouse of drexel 
burnham lambert inc another victim of the scandal which collapsed 
earlier this year 
contrary to milkens claims of a modest humble life in which 
money was secondary the prosecution said he was obsessed with 
wealth and that his enormous compensation devoured much of drexels 
bottom line 
