<TEXT>
eli lilly amp co said it won approval for a 
new device for treating heart patients with clogged arteries a 
catheter that removes rather than flattens the damaging plaque 
the simpson coronary athercath is the first device that cuts 
captures and removes plaque to gain approval by the us food and 
drug administration lilly officials said 
the catheter is manufactured by devices for vascular 
intervention inc a california company lilly purchased for 50 
million last year 
its an important device it has specific uses and it will add 
to the tools we have available but its not going to sweep 
everything else off the table said bruce f waller a cardiac 
pathologist with the indiana heart institute where doctors helped 
test the device 
clogged arteries currently are treated with a balloon catheter 
which doctors insert into a blood vessel and snake to the 
obstructed site the balloon is expanded flattening the plaque 
against the artery wall and allowing more blood to flow through the 
vessel 
researchers have been working on alternatives to balloon 
catheters in part because about onethird of the patients treated 
that way have partial blockage later however waller said some 
studies indicate blockage recurs in up to 40 percent of patients 
treated with the atherectomy catheter 
because of that waller said the new device often will be used 
just before or as a followup treatment with the balloon catheters 
more than 225000 balloon catheter procedures are performed each 
year craig p baskin an analyst with duff and phelps inc in 
chicago estimates the new device could account for about 10 
percent of the operations 
