<TEXT>
bank of boston corp said thursday it expects to 
report a loss of at least 200 million this quarter as it announced 
plans to slash its quarterly dividend by twothirds and cut its 
staff by 1500 employees 
bank of boston joined a growing list of banks that are reducing 
payments to stockholders and curtailing expenses in the wake of a 
declining economy and troubles with real estate loans 
ira stepanian bank of bostons chairman and chief executive 
officer said the moves are necessary to conserve the institutions 
capital base 
we are taking decisive and admittedly painful actions 
stepanian said 
he said the bank expects to show a loss after taxes of 200 to 
250 million this quarter which ends sunday resulting in red ink 
of up to 200 million for the first nine months of the year 
the dividend cut to 10 cents a share from 31 cents is expected 
to conserve about 43 million yearly 
the bank said the expected loss stems from several factors 
including additions to loan loss reserves of 150 million to 200 
million an expected writeoff of bad loans totaling 175 million 
chiefly on real estate and 50 million in charges related to the 
staff reductions and other cutbacks 
bank of boston is a regional bank holding company with assets of 
37 billion it owns banks in massachusetts maine connecticut 
rhode island and vermont 
stepanian said the staff reduction will begin immediately with a 
voluntary plan that offers benefits for employees wishing to leave 
stepanian said the bank is still expanding its retail operations 
and increasing its marketing efforts 
james e moynihan jr an analyst with the investment firm 
advest inc in boston said the announcement was expected the 
market place had discounted this news long ago this stock value 
has been cut in half for the last six weeks he said 
but moynihan added the news really isnt quite as bad as it 
had been thought 
bank of bostons stock fell 37 cents a share to close at 712 
in consolidated new york stock exchange trading thursday 
also thursday bank of new englandwest based in springfield 
laid off 201 of its 1125 employees as part of a plan to cut its 
work force by about 30 percent before the end of the year 
the bank also announced plans to sell four branches and 
consolidate 11 branch offices the moves are part of a recovery 
plan by the banks troubled parent bank of new england corp of 
boston 
stock prices of other banks also fell thursday industry 
analysts attributed it to a spate of bad news recently by a number 
of banks 
on wednesday ncnb corp based in charlotte nc said it 
would report sharply lower earnings this quarter and increase its 
reserves for potentially bad loans 
last week chase manhattan corp the nations secondlargest 
bank said it also expected a quarterly loss and would cut its 
dividend in half 
